  "text": "Node.js implements comprehensive command injection prevention for the child_process module through a multi-layered validation system spanning JavaScript and C++ code. The security mechanism centers on null-byte rejection, which prevents exploitation through embedded NUL characters.\n\n## Validation Entry Points and Functions\n\nThe primary entry points for process spawning are implemented in lib/child_process.js:\n\n1. **spawn(file, args, options)** at line 745: The core spawn function that creates new child processes. It validates all arguments through normalizeSpawnArguments() before passing them to the internal ChildProcess implementation.\n\n2. **exec(command, options, callback)** at line 231: Executes shell commands by calling normalizeExecArgs() which validates the command string for null bytes at line 190.\n\n3. **execFile(file, args, options, callback)** at line 323: Spawns executable files directly, using normalizeExecFileArgs() for argument validation.\n\n4. **fork(modulePath, args, options)** at line 122: Spawns Node.js processes with special handling for IPC, validating execPath at line 142.\n\n## Core Validation Functions\n\nThe validateArgumentNullCheck() function (lib/child_process.js, lines 963-967) is the fundamental security control:\n```javascript\nfunction validateArgumentNullCheck(arg, propName) {\n  if (typeof arg === 'string' && StringPrototypeIncludes(arg, '\\u0000')) {\n    throw new ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE(propName, arg, 'must be a string without null bytes');\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis function checks if any string argument contains null bytes (\\u0000) and immediately throws an error if found. The validateArgumentsNullCheck() function (lines 970-974) extends this by iterating through arrays of arguments, validating each element.\n\n## normalizeSpawnArguments Function\n\nThe normalizeSpawnArguments() function (lib/child_process.js, lines 538-709) performs comprehensive validation:\n\n- Validates the file parameter for null bytes (line 540)\n- Validates all args array elements through validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 556)\n- Validates options.shell for null bytes (line 613)\n- Validates options.argv0 for null bytes (line 597)\n- Validates all environment variable keys and values through nested validateArgumentNullCheck() calls (lines 691-692)\n- Validates cwd through getValidatedPath() (line 568)\n- Validates uid and gid as int32 values (lines 577-584)\n- Validates detached as boolean (line 573)\n- Validates windowsHide and windowsVerbatimArguments as booleans (lines 601-610)\n\n## Internal ChildProcess Implementation\n\nThe ChildProcess class (lib/internal/child_process.js, line 254) represents a spawned child process. Its prototype.spawn() method (lines 354-479) serves as the bridge between JavaScript validation and native code execution:\n\n- Validates the options object (line 357)\n- Processes stdio configuration through getValidStdio() (line 362)\n- Validates serialization mode (line 369)\n- Validates file, args, and envPairs (lines 385-392)\n- Calls native spawn through this._handle.spawn(options) at line 395\n\nThe _handle property is a native Process object created at line 266.\n\n## Native C++ ProcessWrap Implementation\n\nThe src/process_wrap.cc file implements the ProcessWrap class (line 51), which is the C++ native binding for process spawning. The ProcessWrap::Spawn() method (lines 153-310) handles the final validation and system-level spawning:\n\n- Extracts and validates uid and gid as int32 values (lines 171-188)\n- Retrieves the file parameter from options (lines 193-197)\n- Checks for Windows batch file exploits on Windows (lines 203-206)\n- Processes args array, duplicating each argument string (lines 209-225)\n- Processes environment pairs (lines 236-251)\n- Parses stdio options through ParseStdioOptions() (line 254)\n- Validates windowsHide and windows_verbatim_arguments flags (lines 256-275)\n- Validates detached flag (lines 277-283)\n- Calls uv_spawn() to actually spawn the process (line 286)\n\n## Permission System Integration\n\nThe ChildProcessPermission class (src/permission/child_process_permission.h, line 13) provides an additional security layer. The ProcessWrap::Spawn() method includes a permissions check at line 158-159:\n```cpp\nTHROW_IF_INSUFFICIENT_PERMISSIONS(\n    env, permission::PermissionScope::kChildProcess, \"\");\n```\n\nThis allows Node.js to restrict child process spawning at runtime through the permissions API.\n\n## Validation Flow Summary\n\nThe complete validation chain is:\n\n1. User calls spawn/exec/execFile/fork\n2. Entry point function validates through normalizeSpawnArguments/normalizeExecArgs\n3. validateArgumentNullCheck is applied to:\n   - The file/command parameter\n   - All args array elements via validateArgumentsNullCheck\n   - options.shell if present\n   - options.argv0 if present\n   - All environment variable keys and values\n4. Validated options passed to ChildProcess.prototype.spawn()\n5. ChildProcess.prototype.spawn validates and calls this._handle.spawn(options)\n6. ProcessWrap::Spawn() receives validated options, applies permissions check, and calls uv_spawn()\n\nThis layered approach ensures that null bytes cannot be injected at any point in the process spawning pipeline, effectively preventing command injection attacks that rely on null-byte exploitation."
}

